'''Ludolf Bakhuizen'''<ref>Name also spelled Ludolf Backhuijzen, Ludolf Backhuizen, Ludolph Backhuyzen, Ludolph Backhuysen, 
Ludolf Bakhuysen</ref><ref name=rkd>[https://rkd.nl/explore/artists/3414 Ludolf Bakhuizen] at the [[Netherlands Institute for Art History]] {{link language|nl|Middle Dutch}}</ref> (28 December 1630&nbsp;– 17 November 1708) was a German-born [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] painter, draughtsman, calligrapher and printmaker.<ref name=oz>{{harvnb|Broos|2017}} </ref> He was the leading Dutch painter of maritime subjects after [[Willem van de Velde the Elder]] and Younger left for England in 1672.  He also painted portraits of his family and circle of friends.<ref name=oz/>

{{anchor|Biography|History}}

==Life==
He was born in [[Emden]], [[East Frisia]], and came to [[Amsterdam]] in about 1650, working as a merchant's clerk and a [[calligrapher]].{{sfn|Houbraken|1718}} He discovered so strong a genius for painting that he relinquished the business and devoted himself to art from the late 1650s, initially in pen drawings. He studied first under [[Allart van Everdingen]] and then under [[Hendrik Dubbels]], two eminent masters of the time, and soon became celebrated for his sea-pieces, which often had rough seas.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=135}}

He was an ardent student of nature, and frequently exposed himself on the sea in an open boat in order to study the effects of storms. His compositions, which are numerous, are nearly all variations of one subject, the sea, and in a style peculiarly his own, marked by intense realism or faithful imitation of nature. In his later years Bakhuizen employed his skills in [[etching]]; he also painted a few examples each of several other genres of painting, such as portraits, landscapes and [[genre painting]]s.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=135}}

During his life Bakhuizen was visited by [[Cosimo III de' Medici]], [[Peter the Great]] and also worked for various German princes.  In 1699 he opened a gallery on the top floor of the famous [[Royal Palace (Amsterdam)|Amsterdam townhall]]. After a visit to England he died in Amsterdam on 17 November 1708.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=135}}

Bakhuizen painted portraits of his large circle of friends. These are of lesser artistic value but provide an insight into his good relations with contemporary scholars and literary figures.<ref name=oz/>

